headline: Bernie Sanders under fire from own staff amid push for $15 minimum wage
subHeadline: Guests: Campaign staffers blast Bernie over wages, demand raises; reaction and analysis on 'The Five.'

utterances.speaker: JESSE WATTERS, HOST
utterances.sentences: Hello, everybody. I'm Jesse Watters along with Emily, Juan, Lisa, and Greg Gutfeld. It's 5 o'clock in New York City, and this is “The Five.” The 2020 Democrat primary is turning into an absolute circus, and CNN is being brutally mocked for making it even worse. CNN losing even more credibility and turning into a game show network by revealing the upcoming debate lineups like this.

utterances.speaker: UNIDENTIFIED MALE
utterances.sentences: We want to randomly draw candidates.

utterances.speaker: UNIDENTIFIED FEMALE
utterances.sentences: I'm going to take them and mix them up so that we can then draw from the candidate box.

utterances.speaker: UNIDENTIFIED MALE
utterances.sentences: Another shuffle. Mix them up.

utterances.speaker: UNIDENTIFIED FEMALE
utterances.sentences: I'm going to give these a good mix.

utterances.speaker: UNIDENTIFIED FEMALE
utterances.sentences: I'm going to give them a good shuffle.

utterances.speaker: UNIDENTIFIED MALE
utterances.sentences: And placed them into the debate night box.

utterances.speaker: UNIDENTIFIED FEMALE
utterances.sentences: We have multiple camera views.

utterances.speaker: UNIDENTIFIED FEMALE
utterances.sentences: You can watch the camera above me, overhead.

utterances.speaker: UNIDENTIFIED MALE
utterances.sentences: Now, I won't look into the box, but you can look into the box through the overhead camera. Let's start to pick the candidates.

utterances.speaker: WATTERS
utterances.sentences: Wow. Tough to watch, because there're so many candidates it's broken into two nights. Facing off on night one, Bernie Sanders and Liz Warren will battle to see who's the biggest socialist. And Greg and I are particularly happy about this. Marianne Williamson will join them on stage to spread the love. And the second night features a rematch between Biden and Kamala Harris. We'll see if Sleepy Joe will actually fight back this time. Greg, I haven't actually seen it because I don't watch CNN until then, I think they made it less interesting.

utterances.speaker: GREG GUTFELD, HOST
utterances.sentences: It is amazing. The serious music made it even funnier. CNN is officially the carnival news network. They've already have the clowns --

utterances.speaker: WATTERS
utterances.sentences: Yes.

utterances.speaker: GUTFELD
utterances.sentences: -- now they've got the attraction. They need to add a dunk tank, pie eating contest, a ring toss where Don Lemon can toss rings on Chris Cuomo's head. You know what CNN is? I feel like I'm being too mean or not mean enough. CNN is the network without close friends, because close friends tell you when you're making a fool out of yourself. You know, hey, that's an obvious toupee Wolf, Oreo. Chris, you're not funny.  People will, like, come and tell you that your flies down, or whatever, or you need mouthwash, but nobody is telling CNN that you guys look like idiots when you do this stuff.

utterances.speaker: WATTERS
utterances.sentences: MSNBC should really be like, hey, guys, you may want to knock that off. You've got some cabbage --

utterances.speaker: GUTFELD
utterances.sentences: Headline news network should knock on the door.

utterances.speaker: WATTERS
utterances.sentences: Lisa, what do you think the strategy was here? Was it just trying to grab ratings or was it to show transparency?

utterances.speaker: LISA BOOTHE, HOST
utterances.sentences: Well, probably a little bit of both, but primarily for ratings. And, apparently, the special was literally called the draw. I didn't watch it either, but I read the Washington Post write up about it that an eight person panel analyzing like every move throughout the entire hour. You had multiple people pulling the cards and figuring out which candidate would be on what night, so absolutely ridiculous.   But on the substance, what I'm interested in looking at for the debate is how badly diminished Biden and Bernie are by product of who they are on the stage with. Because remember last time, Harris did some -- Kamala Harris did some major damage to Joe Biden. And then, also, if you have Bernie on the stage with Elizabeth Warren, someone who basically has the exact same policy decisions but who's younger and more interesting, and you can see how that could hurt them significantly.

utterances.speaker: WATTERS
utterances.sentences: There was a racial angle to this whole mess, and one of the CNN analyst actually commented on it. Let's watch it and Juan can respond.

utterances.speaker: UNIDENTIFIED MALE
utterances.sentences: It's also worth noting in this -- the most diverse field the Democratic Party has ever had, all of the first nights are white candidates, and the racial diversity is entirely in the second night, which just change the dynamic especially because, obviously, race has been a front and center issue in America this week. It has been in this campaign. It is an issue that is sort of coursing through this Democratic primary.

utterances.speaker: WATTERS
utterances.sentences: What do you think about that, Juan?

utterances.speaker: BOOTHE
utterances.sentences: Does that mean CNN is racist then if they have --

utterances.speaker: GUTFELD
utterances.sentences: Yes. You could them network racist.

utterances.speaker: BOOTHE
utterances.sentences: Is that the rules?

utterances.speaker: JUAN WILLIAMS, HOST
utterances.sentences: Boy, I tell you, you guys see race and everything.

utterances.speaker: WATTERS
utterances.sentences: Oh, someone click that. Click that right there.

utterances.speaker: WILLIAMS
utterances.sentences: But I must say, this was a -- you know, so all the silliness that CNN did, that you guys rightly have mock them for, it was a transparent operation. You can see what was going on. There was no bias implicit -- what kind of criticism or critique is that and of his own network? I don't know. To me it was obvious, you know, that the real news here is, as Lisa was saying, you're going to have Kamala Harris once again up against Joe Biden. So it's gonna be the redo in Detroit, right?  And you want to know what's gonna happen. He said he wasn't prepared last time. Let's see if he's prepared this time. But he's also going to have Cory Booker on that stage, and if you really look at it, Booker has been far more critical of Biden for saying, not about busting, but for saying that he can cross the partisan line, do business, and prove I did business with segregationist in the past. That open a big door. Guess what? Cory Booker did not benefit when Kamala Harris went up in the poll? So, does he sees this now as his opportunity? It's gonna be like a pincer movement around Joe Biden. By the way, some polls came out today, and again, Biden is up. I think Biden's up plus-9 on everybody --

utterances.speaker: GUTFELD
utterances.sentences: But Marianne is coming on strong.

utterances.speaker: WATTERS
utterances.sentences: I'm glad that you brought the polls that just came up, Juan, because Donald Trump up 48 percent approval rating in the NBC News poll. I just wanted to mention that. But moving on, Emily, what do you think about the spectacle?

utterances.speaker: EMILY COMPAGNO, HOST
utterances.sentences: All right. So I did, in my head, winners and losers, and really the only winner that I saw was Kamala Harris, because CNN is obviously a total loser by that whole debacle, and as you've said they're being rightly mock. Bernie and Elizabeth Warren, basically, because of that draw lost the opportunity to challenge Biden on stage. So, for them, they're obviously disappointed. And then Biden, I put him in the loser category because he's going against Kamala again, and also Booker, right? So he's going to be subjective --

utterances.speaker: WATTERS
utterances.sentences: Double take.

utterances.speaker: COMPAGNO
utterances.sentences: Yes, based on his racial record, whatever. I think that for him it would not behoove by the synonym for him to defend his record by really not going there, because it's gonna be death by 1,000 cuts. So what he should do is say, look, I'm not here to litigate the past, I'm on the stage to talk about now, you know, starting with the man in the oval office. Let's move forward. That's a better strategy. And then, for him versus Kamala, it's either Raiders versus Steelers early '70s, or is it 1976 where the Raiders came back and actually beat them.

utterances.speaker: GUTFELD
utterances.sentences: All right.

utterances.speaker: WILLIAMS
utterances.sentences: By the way --

utterances.speaker: WATTERS
utterances.sentences: Sports analogy. Dana's not even here.

utterances.speaker: WILLIAMS
utterances.sentences: Let me just go to the first night, because the first night is really interesting to me --

utterances.speaker: GUTFELD
utterances.sentences: Because of Marianne.

utterances.speaker: WILLIAMS
utterances.sentences: Is that what it is?

utterances.speaker: GUTFELD
utterances.sentences: She's in front. Juan, she jumped in front of Cory, Kiersten, and somebody else -- in New Hampshire. I'm telling you, she's the Trump. She's the Trump, Juan. We should put a bet on her right now.

utterances.speaker: WILLIAMS
utterances.sentences: Wait a minute. She's the Trump? You believe that she's going to be President of the United States?

utterances.speaker: GUTFELD
utterances.sentences: She's the wild card. I'm counting on her getting the nomination.

utterances.speaker: WILLIAMS
utterances.sentences: Really?

utterances.speaker: GUTFELD
utterances.sentences: I was wrong on Trump for -- what? A year and a half, so --

utterances.speaker: BOOTHE
utterances.sentences: Greg's picking up what she's putting down.

utterances.speaker: GUTFELD
utterances.sentences: Yes.

utterances.speaker: WILLIAMS
utterances.sentences: Anyway, I'm interested in Sanders versus Warren.

utterances.speaker: WATTERS
utterances.sentences: Do you think they're going to clash because --

utterances.speaker: WILLIAMS
utterances.sentences: Well, that's an interesting question, because --

utterances.speaker: WILLIAMS
utterances.sentences: Sanders, I think, it's a little bit, as I've said, a rerun. Warren has lots of ideas and new ideas, but it's the same music, right?

utterances.speaker: WATTERS
utterances.sentences: Right.

utterances.speaker: WILLIAMS
utterances.sentences: And the question is, is there more benefit for them in going after each other or teaming up and saying that Joe Biden, he's the problem, he's the old stuff, and we're the new --

utterances.speaker: WATTERS
utterances.sentences: Or focus on Trump the whole time.

utterances.speaker: WILLIAMS
utterances.sentences: Right. And then, the other lane here is Klobucher, Bennett --

utterances.speaker: WATTERS
utterances.sentences: There's a lane there?

utterances.speaker: WILLIAMS
utterances.sentences: Yes, there is. It's a moderate --

utterances.speaker: GUTFELD
utterances.sentences: It's a 12 items or less lane.

utterances.speaker: WILLIAMS
utterances.sentences: And Buttigieg -- does Buttigieg proves he belongs?

utterances.speaker: GUTFELD
utterances.sentences: Yeah.

utterances.speaker: WATTERS
utterances.sentences: Well, he's raised a lot of money, so a lot of other people think that. Greg, going back to CNN --

utterances.speaker: GUTFELD
utterances.sentences: Right, forget the candidates.

utterances.speaker: WATTERS
utterances.sentences: I feel like they have an identity crisis. Are they serious news network, are they the network on New Year's and everybody gets drunk, and they have these little things like they look like Vegas, who are they?

utterances.speaker: GUTFELD
utterances.sentences: It's an interesting thing that has happened to them, because they refused to label whether they're news or commentary. Fox -- everybody knows that we got opinions and we're not, you know, we're not reporters, you know? At least we're spouting off opinions. When you turn on CNN, you have no idea what you're going to get. You'll have a guy report something and then an opinion in the same breath, and then get it wrong or maybe he gets it right, but you can't tell. It's kind of dishonest, and I think that they are. They are in an identity crisis because they used to be something and --

utterances.speaker: WATTERS
utterances.sentences: Right. And you have Don Lemon who's throwing back drink after drink on New Year's and calling Trump you-know-what, and now he's the debate monitor.

utterances.speaker: GUTFELD
utterances.sentences: Don't slander him for drinking.

utterances.speaker: WATTERS
utterances.sentences: I'm sorry.

utterances.speaker: BOOTHE
utterances.sentences: MSNBC used Rachel Maddow in their debates, and then you've got -- or the NBC debates, and then now you've got Don Lemon who is essentially an opinion host as you just pointed out being used in CNN. I mean, can you imagine if Fox did something similar?

utterances.speaker: WILLIAMS
utterances.sentences: Oh, we did.

utterances.speaker: BOOTHE
utterances.sentences: No.

utterances.speaker: WATTERS
utterances.sentences: Who did we have that was that opinionated?

utterances.speaker: WILLIAMS
utterances.sentences: I'm not getting into it.

utterances.speaker: WILLIAMS
utterances.sentences: I just think we should be careful on this one.

utterances.speaker: WATTERS
utterances.sentences: OK. All right, socialist Bernie Sanders is being called a hypocrite by his own campaign. Wait until you hear these details next.

utterances.speaker: WILLIAMS
utterances.sentences: Bernie Sanders repeatedly pledging to raised the minimum wage for workers.

utterances.speaker: SEN. BERNIE SANDERS, I-VT
utterances.sentences: That the working class of this country is sick and tired of working longer hours for lower wages. We have got to raise the minimum wage to living wage.

utterances.speaker: SANDERS
utterances.sentences: We should raise the minimum wage to a living wage, 15 bucks an hour.

utterances.speaker: WILLIAMS
utterances.sentences: But Sanders is apparently not spreading the wealth. Unionized workers on his own campaign reportedly using his rhetoric to demand a pay raise for themselves. They say they're making, quote, poverty wages. And when you do the math it comes out that they earn about $13 an hour. So, Emily, is this something that you can say is hypocritical on the part of Sanders? Or may be more generously that he thinks we need big changes like on health care so that a small business can more easily handle a $15 minimum wage?

utterances.speaker: COMPAGNO
utterances.sentences: Right. I think there's a strong argument and many have called this hypocritical. I think that it's untenable for campaign workers to be paid that kind of $15 an hour given the huge amount of hours that they put into it. And a lot of them doing it for the experience, right? They're doing it because they're committed to the cause. They're putting it on their resumes, the kind of thing where how do you qualify that compensation that we've seen in a lot of different industries as well. I think it does him a disservice based financially just simply on cost- benefit analysis if he is to pay them that much because other campaigns aren't doing the same. That being said, I think his following is so ideologically committed that it would probably do him a good service if he does commit to it in the long run.

utterances.speaker: WILLIAMS
utterances.sentences: But you say other campaigns aren't doing it, so you think that - -

utterances.speaker: COMPAGNO
utterances.sentences: Meaning they're not spending that amount of money. Like, meaning, they're -- you know, they have tons of workers I've said in the beginning that are there for the experience --

utterances.speaker: WILLIAMS
utterances.sentences: So it's not a job. It's not really a job, campaign worker you think?

utterances.speaker: COMPAGNO
utterances.sentences: I think it depends on how you classify it. We saw that with the cheerleader labor lawsuit, right? And you classify as an independent contractor, are you classify as an employee, are you classify as an intern, a volunteer, et cetera, that triggers then federal and state laws as to your compensation. Is that what you're asking?

utterances.speaker: WILLIAMS
utterances.sentences: Yeah, that was interesting because I did not know that about cheerleaders --

utterances.speaker: GUTFELD
utterances.sentences: It's not really a job.

utterances.speaker: WILLIAMS
utterances.sentences: Well, go ahead -- I was going to ask you if you think $15 is enough or how much would you pay people?

utterances.speaker: GUTFELD
utterances.sentences: He is, just by existing, a hypocrite. He's a socialist millionaire with three homes. Wealth is good for him and not for others. You know, I think it's important that he applies the damaging policies that he wants to do to America onto his staff. I think he have to do that, but why won't he? Because he knows when you raise the wages, to your question, you have to reduce the number of jobs, because the pie doesn't grow. You have -- then you have like -- you know, you have four slices of pie instead of six, so two people go. The purpose of the minimum wage is that it's -- the first rung on the employment ladder. To have a lower minimum wage means you have more first rungs with the intention that you don't stay there and you move on. The problem with the left of Bernie Sanders is they see the first rung as the last rung because you're not economically competent. If you raise those wages, you remove those rungs, and that is bad for the country, it's bad for young kids, minorities, women.  People get on that ladder early and faster the better it is for everybody. And you know what? If it's $10 an hour, you're only going to be there for three months, four months.

utterances.speaker: WILLIAMS
utterances.sentences: Wait, so what was the answer? What do you think --

utterances.speaker: GUTFELD
utterances.sentences: I can't remember my answer.

utterances.speaker: GUTFELD
utterances.sentences: I don't remember the question and I don't remember my answer.

utterances.speaker: WILLIAMS
utterances.sentences: Is $15 too much? And if it's so, then what do you think would be enough?

utterances.speaker: GUTFELD
utterances.sentences: I think they should get -- you know, I think they should get $150 an hour, right? Or maybe $1500 an hour, I mean, who's to say?

utterances.speaker: WILLIAMS
utterances.sentences: Thank you, Santa.

utterances.speaker: WATTERS
utterances.sentences: But, Juan, he raised more than anybody since January 1st. He has, I think, $36 million raised in the first six months. So he can afford 15, he can afford 20, he can afford 25. It's how much you want to pay these people and still have money in the bank to win the nomination. It's not like we're going to sit around here and pick a number, Juan. How much do you think? How much do you think?

utterances.speaker: WILLIAMS
utterances.sentences: Well, the reason --

utterances.speaker: WATTERS
utterances.sentences: The guy that's running the campaign should decide.

utterances.speaker: WILLIAMS
utterances.sentences: No, no, no. But, I mean, yesterday, in Congress, the House, in fact, said $15 is appropriate. But the Senate is not going to do it.

utterances.speaker: WATTERS
utterances.sentences: I worked for a campaign and they paid me less than minimum wage and no health insurance.

utterances.speaker: GUTFELD
utterances.sentences: What campaign?

utterances.speaker: WATTERS
utterances.sentences: And --

utterances.speaker: WILLIAMS
utterances.sentences: It was Juan Williams for president.

utterances.speaker: WILLIAMS
utterances.sentences: Wait, you asked for back pay --

utterances.speaker: WATTERS
utterances.sentences: I asked for back pay. My parents made me ask for back pay, and the guy looked at me like get the hell out of here.

utterances.speaker: GUTFELD
utterances.sentences: What campaign?

utterances.speaker: WATTERS
utterances.sentences: It was the Pataki reelection campaign, and I was with Dori Irizarry. She was the attorney general candidate running against Ellie Spitzer.

utterances.speaker: GUTFELD
utterances.sentences: Oh. Well, you were on the right side then?

utterances.speaker: WATTERS
utterances.sentences: Sure, but we lost by 30. Sure.

utterances.speaker: WILLIAMS
utterances.sentences: I wasn't going to mention -- go right ahead.

utterances.speaker: BOOTHE
utterances.sentences: I've worked on multiple campaigns. If you're an intern or you're just simply canvassing, you do not deserve to get paid $15 per hour. And, look, the problem here is in the letter the staffer said, you know, we cannot build the largest grassroots organization if we're being paid poverty level, but it's counterintuitive because you can't build the largest grassroots campaign that you want to build if you're paying people that much who are entry level positions and, quite frankly, don't deserve $15 an hour just for handing out flyers. That's ridiculous. So it's counterintuitive as to what Greg is saying. If you're asking to get paid that much for these, you know, low-level positions, you're going to have to make tough choices for the campaign and not be -- not really to run as strong of an campaign as you want to run.

utterances.speaker: WILLIAMS
utterances.sentences: As I recall, you are a campaign consultant, and that money should go to the campaign consultant --

utterances.speaker: WATTERS
utterances.sentences: Yeah.

utterances.speaker: WILLIAMS
utterances.sentences: -- is that what you're saying?

utterances.speaker: GUTFELD
utterances.sentences: Yeah

utterances.speaker: WILLIAMS
utterances.sentences: Yes, I think that's what she said.

utterances.speaker: BOOTHE
utterances.sentences: That would be nice if I was still doing that. But, no, I mean, it's just counterintuitive because you can't go out there and run the kind of campaign that he want with the sheer amount of volunteers that they're looking to use and pay those people $15 per hour.

utterances.speaker: WATTERS
utterances.sentences: It's counterintuitive, Juan.

utterances.speaker: WILLIAMS
utterances.sentences: One last question for you, my friend.

utterances.speaker: BOOTHE
utterances.sentences: Did I say that enough or should I say it again?

utterances.speaker: WILLIAMS
utterances.sentences: Is it hypocritical on Bernie's part and more so than Trump hiring illegal immigrants?

utterances.speaker: WATTERS
utterances.sentences: Well, he didn't know they're --

utterances.speaker: WILLIAMS
utterances.sentences: Oh.

utterances.speaker: WATTERS
utterances.sentences: -- status, Juan.

utterances.speaker: WILLIAMS
utterances.sentences: I see.

utterances.speaker: WATTERS
utterances.sentences: You're not allowed to ask that.

utterances.speaker: WILLIAMS
utterances.sentences: That's right, no question here on “The Five.” Up next, America celebrating the 50th anniversary of the moon landing, I love it, but some of the media criticizing how America got there. That's next on “The Five.”

utterances.speaker: BOOTHE
utterances.sentences: Welcome back. Well, some in the media are celebrating the 50th anniversary of the moon landing by bashing America. The New York Times is actually praising the Soviet Union for equality and diversity in the space race. The Times patting the Soviets on the back for beating the U.S. by sending the first man, first woman, first Asian man, and black man into orbit. The Washington Post also joining in by tweeting, the culture that put man on the moon was intense for fun -- or intense fun, family unfriendly, and mostly white and male. Juan, I'm going to start with you on this. You look at the 50th anniversary of landing on the moon, it's the epitome of American greatness. So why use this moment to denigrate it to, you know, racist and sexist -- and sexism?

utterances.speaker: WILLIAMS
utterances.sentences: Well, I would think it's inappropriate in some regards because - - first of all, I think this is a twitter comments, so I don't think these were larger nets. So I would say --

utterances.speaker: WATTERS
utterances.sentences: Oh, I thought it was an article.

utterances.speaker: WILLIAMS
utterances.sentences: If this is really about saying, oh, the New York Times, the Washington Post --

utterances.speaker: BOOTHE
utterances.sentences: New York Times was an article.

utterances.speaker: GUTFELD
utterances.sentences: Both of them were articles. They tweeted out the articles.

utterances.speaker: WILLIAMS
utterances.sentences: Tweeted, OK.

utterances.speaker: GUTFELD
utterances.sentences: Yeah, yeah, but they were real, like the moon landing.

utterances.speaker: WILLIAMS
utterances.sentences: I know you have trouble with the moon landing. But I would say, look, I think it's possible to say this was a great moment for our country, one in which we can all be proud. And at the same time say, yeah, guess what? These were all white men, overwhelmingly. In fact, I think, they're mostly Germans. And women participate for the largest part. I mean, they have a movie, hidden figures, about some black women who had some mathematical -- but for the most part, that's what it was. So that's the reality. That's the historical fact.

utterances.speaker: BOOTHE
utterances.sentences: Greg?

utterances.speaker: GUTFELD
utterances.sentences: You know, a totalitarian regime kills tens of millions of people, but first woman in space, we'll forget about everything, OK? You guys are morally superior even though you starved -- how many? Forty, fifty million people? I don't know. But, hey, you got a woman into space before we did, so everything is cool. Remember the guy who landed like a spacecraft's last camera on a comet? Remember that story? Do you remember that? And it was an amazing thing. First guy to land -- like it was a spacecraft on a comet. This was like 4 years ago. We did it on “The Five” --

utterances.speaker: COMPAGNO
utterances.sentences: The little prince?

utterances.speaker: GUTFELD
utterances.sentences: The guy was shamed and humiliated because of the shirt he wore. Don't you remember this story? The guy had -- oh, Jesus. The guy had pictures of women on his shirt, and he got shamed and humiliated. He broke down in tears. And he was like -- he was a hero, but because he wore the wrong shirt, they rip him to shreds because he was not woke enough. We're in a universe now where everything is racist, so almost nothing can be really racist. And so man's greatest technical achievement is now white privilege. You can reduce anything from D-day, to solving poverty, to increasing food abundance, inventing the automobile, to -- just stupid white men. This is so silly and bad. And it reelects Trump, because he rode in on destroying this kind of thinking.

utterances.speaker: WATTERS
utterances.sentences: I bet the female Russian cosmonaut went into space because she was starving. She could not eat in Russia.

utterances.speaker: GUTFELD
utterances.sentences: But you guys don't remember this story?

utterances.speaker: WATTERS
utterances.sentences: No, we don't remember. Did you do a monologue on it, Greg?

utterances.speaker: GUTFELD
utterances.sentences: Yes, I did.

utterances.speaker: WATTERS
utterances.sentences: That's why you remember it.

utterances.speaker: GUTFELD
utterances.sentences: We -- you were tweeting this story to everybody here. Tweet it to them so they'll know.

utterances.speaker: WATTERS
utterances.sentences: I have three theory on this. One, the Washington Post and the New York Times have gone crazy. They've literally gone off the deep end and they're nuts. Number two, they're purposely ignoring real stories like investigating the thousands of Democrats that are running for president, or the connections between Epstein and Bill Clinton, or -- I don't know, Omar allegedly marrying her brother. Stories that actually take a little guts and shoe leather, and actually might hurt Democrats, so they do this little silly stuff, or they're just trolling us. This is like so bad --

utterances.speaker: GUTFELD
utterances.sentences: Yeah, it's true.

utterances.speaker: WATTERS
utterances.sentences: -- it's an onion article that will go viral because all of the conservatives are like what the -- and the people at MSNBC are like, oh, let's do a segment on this. And that's what they're trying to do.

utterances.speaker: BOOTHE
utterances.sentences: Emily?

utterances.speaker: COMPAGNO
utterances.sentences: I grew up with that photo on my wall, and I wanted to be an astronaut, and I wanted to be a fighter pilot --

utterances.speaker: COMPAGNO
utterances.sentences: Yep. And I went to aviation challenge. I did all of that stuff.

utterances.speaker: GUTFELD
utterances.sentences: You aren't good enough, were you? You're too short?

utterances.speaker: BOOTHE
utterances.sentences: Here's a photo.

utterances.speaker: WILLIAMS
utterances.sentences: Look at you.

utterances.speaker: GUTFELD
utterances.sentences: Where are you in there? Where are you?

utterances.speaker: COMPAGNO
utterances.sentences: That's aviation challenge, Alabama. My point is this --

utterances.speaker: GUTFELD
